/*
Problem: Search Insert Position

Definition:
Given a sorted array of distinct integers and a target value,
return the index if the target is found.
Otherwise, return the index where it should be inserted.

Approach:
This problem is equivalent to finding the Lower Bound.
Find the first index where nums[index] >= target.
If no such index exists, return n.

Time Complexity: O(log N)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int searchInsert(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;
        int ans = n;

        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] >= target) {
                ans = mid;
                end = mid - 1;
            } else {
                st = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Mistakes I Made While Learning:

1. Created a separate 'insert' variable.
   Better:
   This problem is exactly the Lower Bound problem.
   Use 'ans' directly.

2. Used:
   insert = mid - 1;
   Correct:
   ans = mid;
   (The insertion position is the current index.)

3. Used:
   insert = mid + 1;
   Correct:
   Continue Binary Search.
   The insertion position is decided only after the search completes.

4. Thought insertion always happens at the end.
   Actually, insertion can happen:
   - At the beginning (index 0)
   - In the middle
   - At the target's existing index
   - At the end (index n)

5. Learned:
   Search Insert Position = Lower Bound

6. Initialized:
   int insert;
   Better:
   int ans = n;
   (If no element >= target exists, insert at the end.)

Key Concept:
Lower Bound -> First element >= target
Search Insert Position -> First valid insertion index
Both use the same Binary Search template.
*/

/*
Possible Optimization:
This is already the optimal Binary Search solution with O(log N) time and O(1) space.
*/
